SIMPLE: emergence
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Emergence
<hw>E*mer"gence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Emergences</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>The act of rising out
of a fluid, or coming forth from envelopment or concealment, or of
rising into view; sudden uprisal or appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The white color of all refracted light, at its very first
<qex>emergence</qex> . . . is compounded of various colors.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir I. Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When from the deep thy bright <qex>emergence</qex> sprung.</q>
<rj><qau>H. Brooke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Emergency</ent>⟦br⟧
